Recall the following theorem mentiond in class on Tuesday.

\begin{framed}
\begin{thm}[Quotient by discrete group action]\label{T:discrete_action}
Let $G$ be a discrete group that acts smoothly, freely, and properly on a smooth manifold $M$. Let $\pi: M \to M/G$
be the quotient map.  Then
\begin{enumerate}[(a)]
 \item The topological quotient $M / G$ is Hausdorff and second countable.
 \item Any point $p \in M$ is covered by a smooth chart $(U_p, \phi_p)$ for which $g.U_p \cap U_p = \emptyset$ for all $g \in G$.  Hence $\mathfrak{A} := \{(\pi(U_p),\phi_{g.p} \circ (\pi|_{U_{g.p}})^{-1})\}_{p \in M, g \in G}$
 is a well-defined collection of charts on $M / G$.
 \item The collection $\mathfrak{A}$ is a smooth atlas on $M / G$.
\end{enumerate}
\end{thm}
\end{framed}


\begin{prob}
 Prove Theorem \ref{T:discrete_action}.
\end{prob}



